# Compose base UI (mandatory for frontend)

Whenever you create or edit frontend UI, build from existing design-system primitives. Do not invent one-off controls, layouts, or visual languages that drift from the app.

## Source of truth

**Base primitives**: `frontend/src/components/ui/*`

Use these first: Button, Input, Textarea, Select, Label, Checkbox, CheckboxList, RadioGroup, Badge, Card, Dialog, AlertDialog, Alert, Accordion, Tabs, Popover, Tooltip, DropdownMenu, Command, FormSection, WizardContainer, Separator, Skeleton, Progress, ScrollArea, Slider, Collapsible, Resizable, MarkdownEditor, Sonner.

Feature UI belongs in `frontend/src/components/<feature>/` and **must compose** the primitives above (and existing feature components). It must not reimplement them.

## Rules

1. **Search before create** — Before adding any new component or styled control, search `components/ui` and neighboring feature folders for an existing match or near-match.
2. **Compose, don’t invent** — Build screens from Button, Input, Card, Dialog, FormSection, etc. Prefer `variant` / `size` / props over new wrappers that restyle from scratch.
3. **Extend the base when shared** — If a pattern will be reused (or already appears twice), add or extend a primitive in `components/ui` (or a shared feature component). Do not leave a third visual dialect in a feature folder.
4. **Match neighbors** — Copy structure, spacing tokens, and control choices from the closest existing similar surface. Same jobs → same components.
5. **className is for layout, not a new design system** — Use `className` for placement/flex/truncate. Do not use it to rebuild buttons, inputs, badges, or dialogs with raw borders, shadows, and custom heights.

## Do

- Import from `@/components/ui/...`
- Reuse FormSection for labeled form blocks; Dialog/AlertDialog for modals; Card only when interaction needs a container
- Add a missing variant to the existing primitive when one size/style is insufficient
- Extract a shared feature component when two feature screens need the same composed block

## Do not

- Hand-roll `<button>`, `<input>`, or modal markup when a ui primitive exists
- Create `FancyButton`, `MyModal`, `CustomBadge`, or similar that duplicates ui/* with different padding/radius/colors
- Fork a second visual style for project vs source (or any sibling) screens
- Copy-paste a large JSX block and tweak colors/spacing instead of sharing a component
- Introduce a new color palette, radius scale, or control height outside existing tokens / ui defaults

## Examples

```tsx
// ❌ BAD — one-off control
button className="rounded-xl bg-indigo-600 px-4 py-2 text-sm shadow-lg"

// ✅ GOOD — compose the primitive
<Button variant="default" size="sm">Save</Button>
```

```tsx
// ❌ BAD — custom modal shell
div className="fixed inset-0 ..."; div className="rounded-2xl border bg-white p-6 ..."

// ✅ GOOD
<Dialog>
  <DialogContent>...</DialogContent>
</Dialog>
```

```tsx
// ❌ BAD — ad-hoc form layout with raw labels/inputs
// ✅ GOOD — FormSection + Label + Input/Select from ui/*
```

## Before finishing a UI change

- [ ] Searched `components/ui` and nearby feature components for an existing primitive
- [ ] New UI is composed from base/feature components, not hand-rolled controls
- [ ] No new parallel button/input/modal/badge implementation
- [ ] Any reusable pattern lives in `components/ui` or a shared feature component
- [ ] Visual density/tokens still match `compact-ui` and existing neighbors
